  title="Knowledge Bases: The Complete Guide"
  description="Learn what a knowledge base is, how to build one, and how to use it to improve your productivity. The comprehensive resource for understanding knowledge management systems."
>
  <Container className="flex flex-col gap-y-16 pb-20">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: "Knowledge Bases" }]} />
    
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <SectionHeader
        title="The Complete Guide to Knowledge Bases"
        description="Everything you need to understand, build, and optimize knowledge bases for your team or business. From basic concepts to advanced implementation strategies."
        level={1}
      />
    </div>

    <!-- Intro Section with Substantial Content -->
    <div class="max-w-3xl prose prose-lg">
      <p class="text-lg/relaxed text-black/70 leading-relaxed">
        A knowledge base is a centralized repository of information that organizations use to store, 
        organize, and share knowledge with their teams and customers. Whether you are building an 
        internal wiki for your employees or a customer-facing help center, understanding the fundamentals 
        of knowledge management is essential for modern businesses.
      </p>
      <p class="text-black/70 leading-relaxed mt-4">
        In today's information-driven economy, organizations generate vast amounts of data, documentation, 
        and institutional knowledge. Without a proper system to capture, organize, and distribute this 
        information, valuable insights get lost, employees waste time searching for answers, and customer 
        support becomes inefficient. A well-designed knowledge base serves as the single source of truth 
        for your organization, ensuring that the right people have access to the right information at 
        the right time.
      </p>
      <p class="text-black/70 leading-relaxed mt-4">
        The concept of knowledge bases has evolved significantly over the past two decades. What started 
        as simple document repositories has transformed into sophisticated, AI-powered platforms that 
        can understand context, provide intelligent recommendations, and even generate new content. 
        Modern knowledge bases integrate with your existing tools, support real-time collaboration, 
        and adapt to how your team actually works.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Main Content Sections -->
    <div class="max-w-3xl flex flex-col gap-y-16">
      <!-- Section 1: What Is a Knowledge Base? -->
      <section class="border-t border-black/10 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black mb-5">What Is a Knowledge Base?</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>
            At its core, a knowledge base is a self-service online library of information about a product, 
            service, department, or topic. It helps customers and employees find answers to common questions 
            without needing to contact support or colleagues directly. Think of it as a digital encyclopedia 
            specifically tailored to your organization's needs and expertise.
          </p>
          <p>
            The architecture of a knowledge base typically consists of several key components working together. 
            First, there's the content layer, where your articles, documents, and resources live. This content 
            is organized through a hierarchical structure of categories and subcategories, making it navigable 
            even as your knowledge base scales to thousands of articles. Then there's the search functionality, 
            which uses algorithms to understand user intent and surface the most relevant content. Modern 
            knowledge bases also include analytics to track what users are searching for, which articles are 
            most helpful, and where gaps in your content exist.
          </p>
          <p>
            Knowledge bases serve different purposes depending on their audience. An internal knowledge base 
            might focus on company policies, standard operating procedures, and tribal knowledge that employees 
            have accumulated over years of experience. An external knowledge base, on the other hand, typically 
            focuses on product documentation, troubleshooting guides, FAQs, and best practices that help 
            customers succeed with your product or service.
          </p>
          <p>
            The effectiveness of a knowledge base is measured not just by the volume of content it contains, 
            but by how easily users can find what they need. A knowledge base with 100 well-organized, 
            clearly-written articles is often more valuable than one with 1,000 poorly structured documents. 
            This is why content strategy, information architecture, and user experience design are critical 
            components of knowledge base success.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
          href="/resources/knowledge-bases/what-is"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-medium text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 transition-colors group mt-5"
        >
          Read the full guide
