          </svg>
        </a>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: Types of Knowledge Bases -->
      <section class="border-t border-black/10 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black mb-5">Types of Knowledge Bases</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>
            Knowledge bases come in various forms depending on their purpose and audience. Understanding 
            the different types helps you choose the right approach for your organization's needs. The 
            landscape of knowledge management has expanded to include specialized solutions for different 
            use cases, industries, and organizational structures.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Internal Knowledge Bases</strong> are designed for employees and internal stakeholders. 
            These systems house proprietary information, company policies, employee handbooks, training 
            materials, and process documentation. They often integrate with HR systems, project management 
            tools, and communication platforms. Security is paramount for internal knowledge bases, with 
            access controls that ensure sensitive information is only available to authorized personnel. 
            These systems help preserve institutional knowledge as employees join and leave the organization, 
            reducing the impact of turnover on organizational memory.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>External Knowledge Bases</strong> are customer-facing systems designed to help users 
            help themselves. These typically include product documentation, troubleshooting guides, FAQs, 
            video tutorials, and community forums. The goal is to reduce support ticket volume while 
            empowering customers to find solutions quickly. External knowledge bases often feature public 
            search engine optimization to ensure customers can find answers through Google and other search 
            engines, not just through your website's navigation.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Hybrid Knowledge Bases</strong> serve both internal and external audiences with shared 
            infrastructure but differentiated access and content. This approach is common in organizations 
            where product documentation is relevant to both customers and support staff, or where certain 
            internal processes have external implications. Hybrid systems require careful content governance 
            to ensure information is appropriately segmented while avoiding duplication.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>AI-Powered Knowledge Bases</strong> represent the cutting edge of knowledge management 
            technology. These systems use natural language processing to understand user queries, machine 
            learning to improve search results over time, and generative AI to create new content or 
            summarize existing information. They can provide conversational interfaces that feel more like 
            chatting with a knowledgeable colleague than searching a traditional database.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
