      <!-- Section 3: Internal vs External -->
      <section class="border-t border-black/10 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black mb-5">Internal vs External Knowledge Bases</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>
            The distinction between internal knowledge bases (for employees) and external knowledge bases 
            (for customers) shapes your content strategy, access controls, and success metrics. While both 
            types share common underlying technology, their purposes, audiences, and implementation details 
            differ significantly.
          </p>
          <p>
            Internal knowledge bases focus on operational efficiency and institutional memory. They contain 
            information that is often proprietary, confidential, or only relevant to employees. This includes 
            detailed process documentation that might change frequently, internal contact directories, 
            project documentation, meeting notes, and strategic planning documents. The tone of internal 
            content is typically more casual and assumes familiarity with company culture and terminology. 
            Success metrics for internal knowledge bases focus on employee productivity, time saved, and 
            reduction in repetitive questions.
          </p>
          <p>
            External knowledge bases, by contrast, are public-facing marketing and support tools. Every 
            article is an opportunity to demonstrate expertise, build trust with potential customers, and 
            improve search engine rankings. External content must be polished, professional, and accessible 
            to users with varying levels of technical expertise. Success is measured through customer 
            satisfaction scores, reduction in support tickets, and organic traffic growth. External 
            knowledge bases also serve a sales function, helping prospects understand your product's 
            capabilities before they ever speak with a sales representative.
          </p>
          <p>
            Many organizations maintain both types simultaneously, with careful curation of what content 
            belongs where. Some information starts as internal documentation and gets refined for external 
            publication once it has been tested and proven valuable. This workflow ensures external content 
            is accurate and comprehensive while preserving the agility of internal documentation.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
