        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black mb-5">Benefits of Knowledge Bases</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>
            Implementing a knowledge base can reduce support tickets by up to 60%, improve employee 
            onboarding, and preserve institutional knowledge. The benefits extend across every department 
            and touchpoint in your organization, creating compounding returns on your investment in 
            knowledge management infrastructure.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>For Customer Support:</strong> A well-maintained knowledge base is your first line of 
            defense against support ticket volume. When customers can find answers to common questions 
            without contacting support, your team can focus on complex issues that truly require human 
            intervention. This reduces costs, improves response times for critical issues, and increases 
            customer satisfaction through immediate answers. Studies show that 70% of customers prefer 
            self-service over contacting support, making a knowledge base essential for meeting customer 
            expectations.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>For Employee Onboarding:</strong> New employees face a steep learning curve when joining 
            an organization. A comprehensive internal knowledge base accelerates onboarding by providing 
            self-paced access to company information, processes, and historical context. Instead of 
            interrupting colleagues with basic questions, new hires can find answers independently, 
            allowing them to become productive more quickly while reducing the burden on existing team 
            members.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>For Knowledge Retention:</strong> Organizations lose valuable institutional knowledge 
            every time an experienced employee leaves. Without a knowledge base, that expertise walks out 
            the door. By systematically documenting processes, decisions, and tribal knowledge, you create 
            a permanent record that persists regardless of personnel changes. This is particularly valuable 
            for complex processes, niche technical knowledge, and historical context that isn't obvious 
            from current systems.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>For Consistency:</strong> When everyone has access to the same information, you ensure 
            consistency in how work is performed, how customers are served, and how decisions are made. 
            This reduces errors, maintains quality standards, and ensures that best practices are followed 
            across the organization. Sales teams can quote accurate information, support teams can provide 
            consistent answers, and operations teams can follow standardized procedures.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>For Scalability:</strong> As your organization grows, the complexity of communication 
            increases exponentially. A knowledge base provides a scalable foundation for growth, allowing 
            you to onboard new team members, expand into new markets, and add new products without 
            proportionally increasing the overhead of training and communication. What works for a team 
            of 10 can scale to a team of 1,000 with the right knowledge infrastructure.
          </p>
        </div>
