      <!-- Section 6: How to Structure a Knowledge Base -->
      <section class="border-t border-black/10 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-black mb-5">How to Structure a Knowledge Base</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/70 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>
            The structure of your knowledge base determines how easily users can find information. Learn 
            best practices for organizing content, creating effective hierarchies, and implementing search 
            functionality. A well-structured knowledge base feels intuitive, reducing the cognitive load 
            on users and helping them find answers quickly.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Information Architecture Principles:</strong> Start by understanding how your users 
            think about and search for information. Conduct user research to identify common questions, 
            pain points, and mental models. Use card sorting exercises to understand how users naturally 
            categorize information. Your knowledge base structure should reflect user mental models rather 
            than internal organizational structures, which may not be obvious to external users.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Category Hierarchy:</strong> Organize content into a logical hierarchy of categories 
            and subcategories. Aim for a balance between breadth and depth. Too many top-level categories 
            overwhelm users with choices, while too few make it difficult to find specific content. A 
            good rule of thumb is to have 5-9 top-level categories, with each category containing 
            subcategories that drill down into more specific topics. Ensure category names use language 
            your audience understandsâ€”avoid internal jargon that might confuse users.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Content Templates:</strong> Consistency in content structure helps users know what 
            to expect and scan for relevant information quickly. Develop templates for different content 
            types: how-to guides should follow a consistent format with clear prerequisites, step-by-step 
            instructions, and expected outcomes. Troubleshooting articles should present problems and 
            solutions in a predictable pattern. FAQ pages should group related questions and provide 
            concise, scannable answers.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Cross-Linking Strategy:</strong> Create a web of interconnected content by linking 
            related articles throughout your knowledge base. When a user finds one answer, they should 
            easily discover related topics that might be relevant. This not only improves the user 
            experience but also helps search engines understand the relationships between your content, 
            improving SEO. Include "Related Articles," "See Also," or "Next Steps" sections at the end 
            of articles to guide users through their journey.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Search Optimization:</strong> Structure your content with search in mind. Use clear, 
            descriptive titles that include keywords users are likely to search for. Break content into 
            scannable sections with descriptive headings. Include synonyms and alternative phrasings that 
            users might use when searching. Implement search analytics to understand what users are 
            looking for and identify content gaps where searches return no results.
          </p>
        </div>
